{"ChunkNum": 1, "StartTime": 183.69, "EndTime": 432.04, "Content": "|24|: This is just having coffee. |25|:  The past couple of months have been a little bit of a strain, but by us doing these events frequently, it gives us the opportunity to go ahead and speak to the community member so they know not to be in fear of the police department and let them know that we are here to support them, but at the same time educate them so they understand what the role of law enforcement is with respect to immigration instead of listening to the false narratives that keep getting passed. |26|:  Exiting homelessness is never easy, but a new community is easing the path. |27|: Atlas Apartments in South LA are new, affordable, and already helping. |28|: Council President Marquise Harris-Dawson joined the city's Housing Authority to celebrate this opening. |29|:  We're so excited to be at the grand opening of brand new affordable supportive housing community here in the heart of South LA. |30|: 127 units that will welcome individuals that are exiting homelessness thanks to a partnership between Link Housing, the City of LA, the Housing Authority and the County. |31|:  It's always nice to get to the finish line and cut the ribbon. |32|: But more than that, every time you do one of these buildings, you talk to someone who has a story. |33|: And the story usually goes something like, I thought I might die living in that alley, or I didn't know if I was ever gonna make it out of living out of my car. |34|: Seeing people have hope who've been at their lowest points is absolutely by far the best part of these buildings. |35|:  being homeless, living in a shelter, recovering from making bad decisions and what have you. |36|: And this is like a big relief. |37|: From roughly 2005 to actually right now, I was homeless. |38|: I'm so grateful to the whole organization for all that they're doing. |39|: You know, I'm just eternally forever be grateful. |40|:  The Housing Authority of the City of LA provides affordable housing to Angelenos across our city. |41|: So 110 vouchers have been committed to this site, and that will allow individuals that are extremely low income to be able to live here. |42|: Across the city, we have about 38 projects that will come online in 2025, about 2,000 units. |43|: And this is how we will continue to end homelessness in our city. |44|:  Well, you know, in Council District, we're very excited. |45|: We are confronting the housing crisis head on. |46|: We're building as much or more housing than anywhere else, but we're also trying to do it in a way that makes our neighborhoods even more livable than they are. |47|: So, traffic and safety improvements, making sure we do things like bring in new grocery stores, and many, many other amenities for the neighborhood that makes this a whole place where we can all, one, first and foremost live indoors, but secondly, have a good quality of life. |48|:  The opportunities are limitless. |49|: Any obstacle that's in front of me, I plan to face it head on. |50|: Delivering hope as well as homes in South LA. |51|: Learning more even before starting school with the Los Angeles Public Library. |52|: The library has thought of everything. |53|: Their programs are for everyone, and that means all Los Angeles families and children, including preschoolers. |54|:  at the Los Angeles Public Library. |55|: We have resources for, we like to say birth through infinity, but in terms of back to school specifically, we have a program for pre-kindergarten little ones called Get Ready for Kindergarten. |56|:  We also have story times to help support early literacy across our 72 branch locations as well as at our central library. |57|: Each one is different depending on the children's librarian who's hosting it.", "Embedding": [-0.00059227017, 0.004085122, 0.013418333, -0.015830003, -0.0025358526, 0.03261414, 0.022496466, -0.00364976, -0.0064856596, -0.047593236, -0.028012896, -0.009810609, -0.0013763232