{"ChunkNum": 23, "StartTime": 3799.608, "EndTime": 4169.907, "Content": "|463|: All right. |464|: And listen, we can't forget the man behind the throne, Japan. |465|: Thank you, brother, for being such a domain, for being a positive force and a real partner in this process. |466|: Next up, we're going to invite Reba Stevens to say a few words, longtime community activist who knows Veronica and knows the work that she does firsthand. |467|:  Good morning, honorable council members. |468|: My name is Reba Stevens. |469|: I'm a community advocate and a resident in the Spa Six community. |470|: It is my honor to stand here before you today as we recognize and celebrate the incredible contributions of Veronica Lewis. |471|:  For many years, Veronica served as the director of Hoppix with unmatched dedication, vision, and compassion. |472|: Her leadership not only strengthened an organization, but it also uplifted an entire community. |473|: She has been a tireless advocate for unhoused individuals and families, ensuring that people receive not only housing,\n|474|:  but also dignity, hope, and opportunity. |475|: Veronica Lewis's legacy is one of service, collaboration, and impact. |476|: She built bridges across systems and sectors, always keeping people at the center of her work. |477|: This exemplifies in her leadership as the founder of the Spa Six Homeless Coalition. |478|:  that's going on right now, where she brought together a diverse group to create more coordination and effective response to houselessness in South Los Angeles. |479|: She has inspired so many of us, myself included, to keep pushing for equity and justice in South Los Angeles. |480|:  Today, as she transitions in her journey, we don't just want to celebrate the work that she's done. |481|: We want to also honor the countless lives that she's changed by her unwavering commitment to the cause. |482|: Veronica Lewis, you're a golden thread in the tapestry of my life. |483|: And I want to thank you for your leadership. |484|:  for your heart, for your dedication and commitment, and for all of the things in which you have bestowed in my life as an advocate. |485|: Thank you. |486|: And thank you, Councilmember Price, for this moment. |487|: Thank you. |488|: And now our shero, Veronica Lewis. |489|:  Thank you so much. |490|: Good morning, City Council. |491|: Thank you, Council Member Price and the whole council for recognizing the work that I have done. |492|: There is so much despair in our city. |493|: There are so many people suffering. |494|: There are injustices happening every second, in particular to people who look like me, black and brown folks. |495|: And there is so much harm that's being done. |496|:  by the systems when we just allowed the status quo to continue. |497|: And so I'm grateful for the recognition, but the reality is everywhere, every time I showed up anywhere in the course of the 21 years I was with this organization, it was to change the status quo. |498|:  to undo the harm, to push against the norms, to push against the narratives and the ideologies and the biases that have led our systems to hurting so many families and so many people. |499|: And so I'm so grateful for the partnership I've enjoyed for so many years with the City of LA. |500|:  In particular, council districts 8, 9, 10, and 15 have been our closest partners in this work, but also reaching across and working with CD4 and folks that were well outside of South LA just to push for change. |501|: And so I am so honored that tens of thousands of lives have been saved. |502|: And under my leadership, hundreds of lives have literally been saved from overdose reversals through our harm reduction street work. |503|:  and all kinds of things, but I'm really grateful that we are making progress. |504|: It's slow, and especially in this climate in our nation right now, the notion of really still digging in, appreciating and being aware and making changes to all of the inequities that exist within our communities\n|505|:  it's really important. |506|: So I appreciate that this council has not completely turned a blind eye to addressing racial inequities, gender inequities, income inequities, socioeconomic challenges, because right now more so than ever, the most vulnerable people living in the city of LA need our help. |507|: And so while I have walked away from something I've built and grew and loved and I'm very proud of, and it's a part of my legacy and my prayers that it will continue to be\n|508|:  beacon of light, I encourage everybody sitting here, elected or not, to make sure that we remember that people need our help, people are dying, people are suffering, and it's not a handout. |509|: Humanity should be at the center of the way that we approach everything, including homeless services, social services,\n|510|:  And we need to continue to make sure folks that have been impacted most negatively by the system are supported through our efforts, through our neighborly kindness, through the legislation and the policies and the ordinances, through your funding, your resource allocations. |511|:  I'm still here fighting.", "Embedding": [-0.00044728306, 0.020293014, -0.0035801672, 0.016739206, -0.0015276353, 0.05830724, 0.028757932, 0.06432851, 0.0034576303, 0.0097015165, 0.021455571, 0.014774069, 0.004428774, -0.010181816, -0.0124916155, 0.020260857, -0.024036178, 0.00031775737, -0.019091588, 0.0007017245, -0.0007343345, -0.010812782, 0.12130176, 0.018808125, 0.0060191774, -0.011529106, -0.023919059, 0.045331817, 0.012856564, -0.0008999217, -0.077428415, -0.035916924, 0.018119931, 0.0019140672, -0.0022102958, 0.007160197, 0.00089819875, -0.0066325967, -0.035714477, 0.003312069, 0.021497743, 0.02981965, -0.0024031138, 0.00996749, 0.0098951105, 0.01900644, 0.0022118946, -0.015236261, -0.0040678233, -0.006754501, 0.010284833, -0.007401247, -0.0023992818, -0.020846577, -0.013915, 0.022650456, 0.026421934, -0.010581351, 0.047139674, -0.0462207