8371066, -0.026133193, 0.008841782, 0.036926933, 0.0012564013, -0.046309106, -0.027618513, -0.01703721, 0.008882662, -0.02276571, -0.014071797, 0.025633758, -0.017584672, 0.0173872, 0.008924161, -0.006585445, -0.009213665, 0.0164403, -0.019398708, 0.010400243, -0.009168528, 0.03871747, 0.01480545, -0.028867152, -0.00016364716, -0.016717067, 0.0036654014, 0.0118859215, 0.0037034766, -0.010920603, -0.0060718386, -0.004421351, -0.015675403, 0.0039554015, 0.013341481, 0.016010944, -0.018671148, 0.0029058424, 0.009196081, -0.042094998, 0.018551724, -0.010986385, 0.022135407, -0.010698926, 0.0046038413, 0.03431801, 0.010232647, 0.013598397, 0.022441095, 0.027485585, -0.00825039, 0.025125109, 0.010854828, -0.013380895, -0.023941334, -0.0062356424, -0.025611922, 0.020004436, -0.0013040552, -0.010533028, -0.024189511, 0.00804783, 0.013664176, 0.01541202, 0.007547584, 0.00020127476, -0.0029468292, -0.049328435, -0.0076695182, 0.010040729]},
{"ChunkNum": 36, "StartTime": 6017.555, "EndTime": 6886.705, "Content": "|817|:  All right. |818|: Next, we'll hear from Councilmember Hernandez of the heart of the city, the first council district. |819|:  How are you like how we'd like great\n|820|:  th th\n|821|:  So sergeants mr. Herman has been removed from council chambers for the balance of this day He is removed from this meeting We will pause until he has exited the council chambers\n|822|:  Mr. Herman, you were ordered removed from the Rules Committee meeting. |823|: You were also ordered removed from a meeting earlier this week. |824|: I would note that as soon as you came into this meeting, for which you are not permitted to be in, because you were on probation when you were removed, that you are continuing to disrupt this meeting. |825|: And you have been ordered removed. |826|:  My apologies, Councilmember Hernandez, Mr. Spindler, and whoever else is in the aisle will ask you to vacate the aisles while this presentation is happening. |827|: Wonderful. |828|: And the floor is yours, Councilmember Hernandez. |829|: Thank you, Council President. |830|: Good morning, everyone. |831|: Buenos dias. |832|: Today, I'm proud to announce that the city of Los Angeles officially recognizes Latino Heritage Month. |833|:  At a time when our communities are under attack, when ICE raids terrorize our neighborhoods, when a racist federal administration fuels division, and when the Supreme Court has given a green light to racial profiling, we are here to stand tall and proud as Latinos in a moment where we are told to shrink and hide. |834|:  Today we will honor two extraordinary Latinos whose lives remind us that the fight for justice takes many forms. |835|: Carlos Montes, a pioneer and Chicano activist and founding member of the Brown Brace, represents decades of direct action, courage, and organizing in the face of injustice. |836|:  Francisco Letilier, an internationally recognized muralist, illustrator, and poet has carried forward the tradition of resistance through art, memory, and storytelling. |837|: Together, they show us that in the struggle for justice, there is a lane for all of us, whether it's in the streets, through organizing, or by creating art, and that, you know, make sure that our stories are never forgotten. |838|:  Tomorrow, we continue the celebration. |839|: We continue the celebration with El Grito at Grand Park from 5 to 11 p.m. |840|: It is our city's largest Latino Heritage Month celebration, a night of culture, music, and community power. |841|: In these dark times, we remember that joy is an act of resistance. |842|: And as this year's Madrina of the event, I hope to see you all there. |843|: I can't wait to see you there, colleagues and everybody from your teams. |844|:  In just a moment, you'll hear from all the Latino council members, or as I've called us, the Latino caucus, who joined me in this chamber today. |845|: We are here and we are proud. |846|: We carry a shared struggle. |847|: Many of us are children of immigrants raised in households that knew sacrifice, hard work, and resilience. |848|: Our presence here is proof of what our parents and grandparents dreamed for us, that despite the obstacles, despite the discrimination, we would claim our place in shaping the future of this city. |849|:  I now would like to invite my colleague, Councilmember Padilla, to share a few words. |850|: Thank you for joining us. |851|:  Good morning, everyone, and thank you, Councilmember Unisys, for bringing this to our chambers today. |852|: And congratulations on being the madrina for this year's El Grito. |853|: I'm honored to join you in celebration of Latino Heritage Month and to uplift two extraordinary individuals whose legacies embody this year's theme of viva la resistencia, reminding us that what we're going through, we've been through it, and we will supersede. |854|:  Carlos Montes is a pioneer Chicano activist and co-founder of the Brown Braids. |855|: Francisco Letir is an internationally recognized muralist, illustrator, and poet. |856|: Though their paths are different, their work has carried the same purpose, advancing justice, advancing our people, and ensuring that our stories are never erased. |857|: Carlos represents the spirit of direct action and organizing. |858|:  From the East LA walkouts to the Chicano moratorium, he stood on the front lines demanding dignity and equality for generations of Chicanos and Latinos to come. |859|: His courage shows us the impact the voices raise, barriers challenged, and communities united in struggle. |860|:  and a history that we can very much learn from. |861|: Francisco shows us the power of art as resistance. |862|: Through his murals, writing, and creative vision, he has turned art into living testaments of identity and resilience. |863|: His work shows how art goes beyond expression. |864|: It is preservation and a bridge between past and future. |865|: There is no single way to properly resist. |866|:  There are those who march, organize, and mobilize, and those who paint, write, and tell our stories. |867|: Both are necessary, both are powerful, and both deserve to be celebrated and acknowledged. |868|:  Because in the struggle for justice, there is a lane for each and every one of us to participate. |869|: We should participate and bring to the table our talents in doing so. |870|: So in a time when there's a target on us, it is important to know more than ever, to be proud and unapologetic of who we are, remember our past, learn from it, and propel forward. |871|:  So thank you, colleagues. |872|: Now, I'd like to introduce our next speaker, who I believe is still taking pictures in the back. |873|: So Council Member Unises, we should go to Council Member Hugo Soto Martinez. |874|: Adelante. |875|:  Thank you so much, Councilwoman Padilla. |876|: And thanks so much, Councilwoman Hernandez, for serving as this year's Madrina for Latino Heritage Month. |877|: And you do it with such grace and with such strength. |878|: I had the honor of doing this last year, and I know it's not an easy job. |879|: Not just putting the event together, but trying to capture the moment and trying to capture the Latino identity is not an easy thing. |880|:  We are indigenous, there are Afro-Latinos, we have Spanish, and so many other different cultures that come together because Latinidad is not something that's easily boiled down to. |881|: We know we're a mix of cultures, histories, cuisines, and traditions. |882|: And so you've managed to pick a theme that I think resonates across all cultures, la resistencia. |883|:  In celebrating resistance, you are celebrating a value that is part of all of us, because we know that our resistance, our resilience, our collective power, and our ability to envision a future is worthy of our struggles. |884|: And I think every single person that identifies a Latino can resonate with those words, especially in a moment like right now, where our culture, our communities, and our identity is under attack against this white nationalist president,\n|885|:  They would like nothing more than to erase us from this country. |886|: And we know that weak man will try to bring us down, but people like Carlos Montes and the Brown Berets like they did before, we know we have to come together in this moment and fight. |887|: And not just among Latinos, but find solidarity among all working people, because we know Latinos are not the only ones under attack in this moment. |888|:  So I'm happy to join you today and mark the start of Latino Heritage Month once more with a rallying cry. |889|: Que viva la resistencia. |890|: Que viva. |891|: Que viva la latinidad. |892|: Que viva. |893|: Que viva el pueblo. |894|: Que viva. |895|: Y que viva los trabajadores. |896|: Que viva. |897|: And now, one of our madrinas from two years ago is here. |898|: And so I want to pass it back to Councilmember from the 7th District, Councilmember Rodriguez. |899|: Thank you. |900|:  Thank you, colleagues. |901|: It's been a pretty eventful day, but I want to thank and congratulate Councilmember Hernandez for being the madrina this year at such a pivotal moment in time for our community. |902|:  What a special time for us to continue to tell the stories of who we are and to share it and remind everybody about the strength of who we are. |903|: And I'm just incredibly grateful and proud of your example in the resistance and being that example for our community. |904|: But this month has extra special meaning. |905|: And I've said many times that heritage months aren't something that we should be just limited to for\n|906|:  30 days, it's something, it's an exercise in the resistance every single day and that is, that's actually even more meaningful today than it ever was before. |907|: So I want to thank you because I know how much this Grito celebration means to our community now more than ever. |908|: I know how special it is and how,\n|909|:  much effort it is and congratulations to you and your staff because I know what an extra lift it is on top of all of the daily grind of the work that we do every day but I will tell you that there's no more special time than to do it right now and I want to thank you and congratulate you for sticking with it to continuing to do it because I think what we need now is that example of solidarity and strength\n|910|:  tomorrow, today, every day, more than ever. |911|: So thank you very much for continuing on and forging forward. |912|: And it's a reminder to the community to, again, this is our moment to stand strong together in solidarity during these most difficult times and be proud of who we are and not hide who we are. |913|: We are what makes this country great. |914|: And no one should ever forget that. |915|: Thank you. |916|:  Thank you for your kind words, colleagues, and thank you for being here today. |917|: We gather here today not just to celebrate heritage, but to affirm our resilience at a time when Latino communities are under attack. |918|: In the last three months alone, ICE has raided parking lots, work sites, churches, and hospitals in Los Angeles with military-style tactics and language. |919|:  We are living in a federal administration that is openly racist, and just this week the Supreme Court ruled again to essentially permit racial profiling, a decision that will put black and brown lives at even greater risk. |920|: That's why honoring Latino committee members like Carlos Montes matters so much. |921|:  Carlos is a co-founder of the Brown Berets and one of the leaders of the East LA Chicano blowouts and a series of walkouts of East Los Angeles high schools to protest against racism and inequality in Los Angeles area high schools. |922|: With the Brown Berets, Carlos organized the first Chicano moratorium protest against the Vietnam War in East LA. |923|:  He has been on the front lines of the Chicano movement for decades, from the walkouts that transformed our schools, to the community defense networks that challenge police abuse, to his mentorship and advocacy on Centro CSO. |924|: His life's work is a testament to what happens when ordinary people organize with extraordinary courage. |925|:  When we honor Carlos, we're honoring Latino history and we're honoring the new generation of Latino activists who will continue to demand justice across Los Angeles today. |926|: It is my great honor to present him with the certificate on behalf of the City of Los Angeles. |927|: Thank you so much. |928|:  Carlos, on behalf of the city of Los Angeles, we want to recognize you for your lifetime of service and commitment to social justice. |929|: As a founding member of the Brown Berets and a leader of the Chicano movement, you have fought tirelessly for the rights of students, workers, and communities of color. |930|: Your courage inspires me and I know inspires a lot of us here in the city. |931|: And you have a vision that is going to continue to take us for generations to resist the attacks on our communities and oppression and to build a more just and equitable Los Angeles. |932|: So thank you so much for your dedication and leadership.", "Embedding": [-0.0004494017, -0.013720902, 0.034067582, 0.00056352746, -0.0014602195, 0.077350706, 0.012169026, -0.010076776, 0.017834136, 0.016198331, 0.033005215, 0.0022659935, -0.0009335302, 0.029382758, 0.01747543, -0.008688084, -0.041546613, -0.05172808, 0.0060894364, -0.0022090706, -0.013325622, 0.0076558813, 0.07998876, 0.02170842, 0.0849025, -0.013729146, -0.023619302, -0.007194662, -0.000987615, 0.004975867, -0.057539195, -0.03756252, -0.0029026559, -0.009352961, 0.0007038678, 0.0033714867, 0.036739532, -0.002970126, 0.027569072, 0.0056290543, 0.011083703, -0.009168958, -0.007685163, -0.006505129, 0.03070515, 0.03257282, -0.012053473, 0.025127815, -0.010790005, -0.020669105, 0.0029205866, 0.00080383156, -0.0043066842, -0.018311264, -0.020200055, 0.019769453, 0.0051618256, -0.003004633, 0.015478417, -0.034981843, 0.0072392067, 0.004281861, -0.035843424, -0.013386677, -0.004794285, -0.024367848, 0.007666899, -0.02385907, -0.005020483, -0.01222111, -0.022345977, 0.0049107578, -0.029556328, -0.01936177, 0.0059292563, -0.0118333, -0.0028306928, 0.021660656, -0.008504715, 0.011007265, 0.003127568, 0.0064122253, 0.0011749591, -0.008930894, -0.0153478095, -0.010364477, 0.033341784, 0.0022433824, -0.017610855, -0.0072439234, 0.013001724, -0.00022902428, -0.0013925772, 0.028194958, 0.0053334255, 0.024119558, -0.007862451, -0.030167447, -0.01925829, 0.0046953084, -0.004291384, -0.025264792, 0.009675252, -0.0069086743, 0.010062051, -0.025500933, -0.010364796, 0.00014820573, 0.0027149152, 0.023542918, 0.014372757, 0.027255498, -0.02241313, -0.021552913, 0.0077069146, -0.016330652, 0.025878588, -0.010606147, 0.004551814, -0.056350894, -0.0015207257, 0.015899297, 0.007318936, -0.0038755669, 0.0006170137, -0.016075462, 0.004601108, -0