{"ChunkNum": 39, "StartTime": 6952.746, "EndTime": 7169.289, "Content": "|956|: You know, Dad, you know, I'm busy. |957|: And then all our young folks are at the ACLU right now talking about the struggle against police brutality because we recently had,\n|958|:  Jeremy Floyd is killed in Boyle Heights in July. |959|: We're working with the family, helping them out, you know, organizing protests at Hollomback police station, you know, like we did in 2016 where five young men were killed by the Hollomback station, right? |960|:  when all the nonprofits are afraid to take on that issue, right? |961|: So, you know, this recognition, you're right, it's about the people, the movement that I happen to be part of. |962|: I'm just a little kid from the border town of El Paso Juarez that got thrown into this nightmare. |963|: I remember the watch rebellion, talking with the\n|964|:  with the black janitors when I was working, you know, and discussing, you know, I was fascinated by the argument. |965|: One was saying, yeah, let's do it. |966|: The other one said, let's not do it. |967|: I was the Rodney King Rebellion. |968|: I was there in front of Parker Center with all the young folks. |969|: All the older generation was saying no justice, no peace picket signs. |970|: The young black,\n|971|:  Chicano Asians were saying, hell no, let's take it on. |972|: So I had to join them, even though it was spontaneous mass anger. |973|: But we learned during the George Floyd rebellion, we were well-organized. |974|: We had bullhorns. |975|: We had banners. |976|: We had trucks. |977|: We united all the Chicano, Black, Asian community to say justice for our community. |978|: So yeah. |979|:  I want to, you know, it's good to say viva la independencia, the struggle against the Spanish colonization, but remember that we suffered a Mexican-American war 1848. |980|: So we have been fighting for, against racist oppression since that time, lynchings, massacres, discrimination, right? |981|: And the struggle continues. |982|: I happen to be part of the 60s, like,\n|983|:  like many of your parents maybe, right? |984|: And thank you all for continuing the struggle here in the City Council, right? |985|: So, you know, I just wanted to point out that it's great to commemorate our struggle. |986|: You know, I was there in the Poor People's Campaign. |987|: I learned. |988|:  about the importance of black and brown unity and uniting all working people together, MLK invited the Mexicans to come before he was assassinated, right? |989|: Some of his reverends didn't want the Mexicans because we didn't believe in so-called nonviolence, right? |990|: So let me kind of wrap it up that, you know, I'm proud of the movement\n|991|:  that we've all created our history, you know, I want to point out that the mega marches of 2006, I was there at 8 o'clock in the morning when I looked up Broadway and it was already packed all the way to city. |992|: How many of you were there? |993|: Raise your hand, you know, the mega marches, right? |994|:  And, you know, the marches against the war in Iraq, right? |995|: I learned from the struggle against the war in Vietnam when our homies came back that I went to high school with with trauma and shrapnel. |996|: And one of them, Andy, showed me his album of all the atrocities they committed. |997|: We tried to help them. |998|:  He ended up dying of a heroin overdose in a garage, an abandoned garage. |999|: That radicalized my generation to say not only U.S. out of Vietnam, but we were controversial. |1000|: We said the Vietnamese struggle needs to win. |1001|:  We supported the struggle of the Vietnamese people. |1002|: And today, yes, today may be controversial, maybe not. |1003|: We support the struggle of the Palestinian people for self-determination, national liberation, and the right of return of all Palestinian refugees and an end to all USA to Israel. |1004|: That's right.", "Embedding": [-0.00032176898, -0.031428102, 0.026