{"ChunkNum": 46, "StartTime": 7437.692, "EndTime": 7643.683, "Content": "|1064|: I mean, what didn't you say that hasn't been said about you? |1065|: For me, representing this district, which is so diverse, it has El Pueblo, it has the fashion district, El Serrano, it has Boyle Heights, I get to witness the energy and the pride of working class, resilient Latino community. |1066|:  You showing up, especially as part of the historic Eastside, is so important. |1067|: You know, co-founder of the Brown Berets, a lifelong activist, tireless organizer, and someone who has never stopped showing up for the community. |1068|: When we set up our CD14 Fires Resilience Hubs at our Boyle Heights Community Field Office, guess who is there every single day? |1069|:  You know, you always pound the pavement. |1070|: You're able to make community anywhere that you go with everyone that's around you. |1071|: And everyone even on our campaign has a story of when they met you or how they got to know you. |1072|: And of course, we always poke fun at you about the walkout movie and whether you got to choose who got to play you in that movie. |1073|: But you know, you always remind us that you keep heritage alive by doing. |1074|:  and you continue that activism and you never let a moment pass by saying what's on your mind and in your heart and you show us what solidarity looks like every single day. |1075|: So thank you so much and thank you for honoring him. |1076|:  Thank you so much. |1077|: Thank you so much, members. |1078|: And thank you, Councilmembers Rodriguez, Padilla, Soto-Martinez, and the leader for our celebration this year. |1079|: Councilmember Hernandez for bringing this. |1080|: And I especially want to thank our council colleagues for centering and lifting in this celebration. |1081|:  the spirit of resistance and the spirit of struggle. |1082|: Because this happens with Black History Month, with other celebrations where some people try to make it about beer or food or dancing or music, and all of those things are great. |1083|: But we have these celebrations and commemorations to remind us of the struggle and how we got to the stage that we are now and how much further we have to go. |1084|:  And I couldn't be prouder. |1085|: This is one of my proudest moments sitting up here to be chairing this meeting as we honor the great Carlos Montes. |1086|: It's rare that you get to see your heroes in the flesh. |1087|: I can remember watching you growing up as a young activist and then\n|1088|:  during my time at the Community Coalition where, you know, Karen Bass would say, yeah, I go back with Carlos, but you know, be careful out there. |1089|: Be careful about getting locked up. |1090|: Don't go too far. |1091|: Don't take it too far. |1092|: But I appreciate you because you embody the spirit of resistance when it's popular, but you also do it when it's not popular. |1093|:  when the media and society says, oh, we're having a good time. |1094|: Why don't you go over there and be quiet? |1095|: Stop bothering us about police brutality. |1096|: Stop raising racism. |1097|: We're trying to celebrate our progress, and here you are continuing to raise issues. |1098|: So I thank you for sticking to the struggle, because it always comes back around.", "Embedding": [-0.00046336406, -0.029684842, 0.008535216, -0.043928403, -0.0017397355, 0.05258391, 0.01829978, 0.0056621367, 0.0046696197, -0.026996352, 0.030302817, 0.0014258451, 0.0012103745, 0.06418746, 0.014288635, 0.033838127, -0.052776255, -0.031783972, 0.01164932, 0.0015644828, -0.013523797, 0.02158236, 0.070440516, 0.040211882, 0.06094585, -0.024333153, -0.02395349, -0.0042168847, -0.005356221, 0.012441365, -0.061114237, -0.054965228, -0.016207958, -0.012963436, -0.00052844157, 0.015365525, 0.028361047, 0.00026717302, 0.028427098, -0.011643823, 0.01979487, 0.017306617, -0.02011681, 0.0034819385, 0.029603964, 0.027437687, -0.008211965, 0.034837093, -0.013133108, -0.0035072898, 0.00311140