020905181, -0.004594865, 0.010755341, -0.017820485, -0.0058173463, 0.021981768, 0.016621228, -0.0058930037, 0.0225057, 5.7875477e-05, 0.005755073, 0.00805586, 0.028941493, 0.0032773966, 0.026571348, 0.017621603, -0.00947348, 0.035683297, -0.015111027, -0.012531126, -0.00087439554, 0.012029065, 0.0013452525, 0.003910888, 0.028595762, -0.012257493, -0.013086131, -0.0013871659, -0.000694949, 0.014911919, -0.010769287, -0.0067712027, -0.0074836477, -0.013716637, 0.01168797, -0.040632084, 0.04142193, -0.0033838237, 0.014540995, 0.021316035, -0.00386691, 0.033979814, 0.00065452134, 9.7884855e-05, -0.0066011106, -0.0105678765, 0.021920381, -0.01800282, -0.045918927, -0.011767739, -0.006150578, 0.01834511, -0.00033980425, -0.007852141, 0.035139408, 0.012162173, -0.026137788, 0.010701995, 0.04371277, -0.023043627, -0.026176218, 0.0065564546, 0.015171877, 0.033071227, 0.015396733, -0.0020306925, 0.0024947284, 0.01881222, 0.007826683, -0.008499521, -0.03630765, 0.036439583, 0.013205701, -0.009221721, 0.017604906, -0.0057930714, 0.006187012, 0.014869229, -0.00330157, 0.016081726, -0.007934787, 0.0012723138, -0.008686785, -0.023566877, 0.0064069554, -0.027276792, 0.019192895, -0.009176297, -0.02224648, 0.01583922, 0.0076831267, -0.0013754669, -0.009655672, -0.01445192, -0.0029134457, 0.037808694, -0.009317867, -0.010477268, -0.013182806, 0.002686541, -0.00405467, -0.0054190913, 0.014914747, 0.0025367457, 0.002385903, 0.01664439, -0.01777312, 0.008248672, 0.0051567573, 0.01085494, -0.03621938, -0.015958756, -0.027691323, 0.009789995, 0.018930422, -0.01918759, -0.004558952, -0.016184898, 0.02108415, -0.014011285, -0.009431601, -0.03217536, 0.00021874471, 0.023232687, 0.012323325]},
{"ChunkNum": 48, "StartTime": 7687.137, "EndTime": 8198.323, "Content": "|1106|: And thank you, Carlos, for being here with us today. |1107|: Latino resistance also lives in our art, murals, poetry, and storytelling that carry memory and connect us across generations. |1108|: And Viva La Resistencia is not about how just we resist today, but it's about recognizing how we resisted in our past generations in different communities in different ways. |1109|:  Many of you have seen our Bridge Art Gallery exhibition, Viva La Resistencia, a celebration of Latino resistance and joy in a time of peril. |1110|: That work would not have been possible without the partnership with the Department of Cultural Affairs. |1111|: Today we have the privilege of unveiling the newest cover of the Latino Heritage Month edition of the DCA booklet and honoring the artists behind it. |1112|: To introduce our second honoree, Francisco Letelier, please join me in welcoming Daniel Tarica, General Manager of the Department of Cultural Affairs. |1113|:  Thank you so much, Councilmember Hernandez. |1114|: It's truly an honor to be here today to celebrate Latino Heritage Month on behalf of the Department of Cultural Affairs. |1115|: In a time when pervasive discrimination continues to negatively impact our communities, lifting up and recognizing the city's rich cultural heritage and legacy through the arts is so important now more than it has been in recent history. |1116|:  Telling those stories and sharing experiences as a city's Latinx community is an important way for us to bring truth to power. |1117|:  Together, we honor the diverse Latinx communities that have shaped Los Angeles, our Southern California region, and across our nation for centuries. |1118|: The community's impact is felt every day through its civic leaders, change makers, entrepreneurs and educators, caregivers and artisans, students and culture bearers, enriching our community in countless ways. |1119|:  This year, we continue the tradition by presenting the 2025 edition of the Latino Heritage Month Calendar and Cultural Guide that recognizes the accomplishments of our actors, our performers, our poets and our writers and our artists. |1120|: It contains visual art and poetry from a wide selection of talented artists emerging and established, as well as many art exhibitions. |1121|:  The generations of artists and storytellers and culture bearers from communities across Latin America and here in Southern California that live here that have shaped our city and while their descendants carry that legacy forward every day through arts and culture as well as through business and civic leadership. |1122|: The guide reflects the partnership of our many collaborators and I want to express our appreciation to our partners for the work of the offices of the mayor, the controller, the city attorney,\n|1123|:  City Council, and very much especially for the work of Councilmember Hernandez and her team. |1124|: So as Councilmember Hernandez mentioned, in addition to the guide, we are also proud to support the work of the Bridge Gallery exhibition with Councilmember Hernandez and her team as well as Altura LA on the Viva La Resistencia. |1125|: It is really a wonderful exhibition and I encourage you all to see it. |1126|:  So before we unveil the artwork of today's Latino Heritage Month calendar and cultural guide, I have the honor of introducing the artist who developed the guide's cover artwork. |1127|: Francisco Letellier is an award-winning visual artist, graphic designer, illustrator, muralist, and poet. |1128|:  Letellier creates art that crosses disciplines and cultures. |1129|: His work blends history with contemporary experiences with an emphasis on the social circumstances that affect our individuals and our communities. |1130|: Mr. Letellier received a Grammy nomination for his work\n|1131|:  on musician Jackson Brown's World in Motion release. |1132|: He has also been recognized through LA Art Corps, as well as through SPARC. |1133|: And we also are very proud of his work, Todas Las Manos, at American University in Washington, DC, that was dedicated by Chilean President Michelle Bachelet. |1134|: Please join me in welcoming el maestro Francisco Letillier. |1135|:  It's so nice to be here and for my artwork to be selected for this wonderful guiding calendar because when you get a chance to look through it, you'll see that we are a city rich in talent and artistic accomplishments. |1136|: So I could be\n|1137|:  waiting for a long time to be on this cover. |1138|: There are so many that deserve to be on it. |1139|: But I just want to tell you a little bit about what inspired me. |1140|: The illustration is called El Cantante, The Singer. |1141|:  And it's inspired by the vibrant culture that was repressed in Chile, where I was born, after the rise of the authoritarian dictatorship that overthrew democracy on September 11, 1973. |1142|:  It led to the imprisonment of thousands and the death of thousands, including my father and many people in my family, relatives and friends. |1143|: Now through arts and culture, Chileans built solidarity and hope. |1144|: They spread information and helped create the social movements that led back to democracy. |1145|:  Inspired by the diversity and knowledge held in the cultures of Los Angeles and across the Americas, my work recognizes travelers, the exchange of ideas, and it affirms our complexities, our celebrations, and our challenges. |1146|: I'm grateful. |1147|:  to this council and the Department of Cultural Affairs for their ongoing efforts to defend and reimagine cultural heritage as a tool for progress and action. |1148|: And today I want to say resistance. |1149|: Que viva la ciudad de Los Angeles. |1150|: Thank you. |1151|:  On behalf of the city of LA we want to recognize Francisco let's yeah, we'll do a picture because we know folks around Thank you, thank you\n|1152|:  We want to recognize you for your extraordinary contributions, Francisco, to the arts and your shared struggle for justice. |1153|: And I want to point something out. |1154|: We're going through authoritarianism, what feels like a takeover here in this country. |1155|: And oftentimes, I know I've said this, it's like, oh, we don't have a playbook. |1156|: What to do? |1157|:  Places like Chile that have survived authoritarianism have playbooks. |1158|: They have showed us what it takes to build community power to survive moments like these. |1159|: So I appreciate you, Francisco, for lifting that up. |1160|: Colleagues, what you've seen today is that Latino resistance is not just about protest. |1161|: It's also about creation. |1162|: It's about building a world where our stories, our struggles, and our joy are reflected back to us in art, in history, and community. |1163|:  Carlos Montes and Francisco Letelier show us two sides of the same coin, the power of action and the power of imagination. |1164|:  That is the spirit of Latino Heritage Month, honoring our past, fighting for our future, and celebrating the beauty and resilience of our people. |1165|: I'm so proud to officially recognize this month as Latino Heritage Month on behalf of the city of Los Angeles, and I hope to see each and every one of you tomorrow at El Grito celebrating with us. |1166|: Colleagues, now please join me in the unveiling of our Latino Heritage Book this year. |1167|:  Thank you. |1168|: Que viva la resistencia. |1169|: Thank you so much.", "Embedding": [-0.00066819007, -0.0248438, 0.014753229, 0.011803041, -0.002376391, 0.054143224, 0.0142690465, -0.010424276, 0.0014728205, -0.007695992, 0.038217075, 0.0021826716, -0.00080320274, 0.008557745, 0.046653654, -0.018009784, -0.08742511, -0.042847972, 0.014199964, -0.0015445584, -0.0031535956, 0.017548986, 0.08124585, 0.047260202, 0.074883774, -0.019409174, -0.013062893, 0.009044583, 0.0071205837, -0.01726397, -0.023931038, -0.02856192, 0.017943135, -0.025568075, -0.0015