{"ChunkNum": 56, "StartTime": 8512.304, "EndTime": 8572.939, "Content": "|1237|:  Hello, speaking general vote comment. |1238|: I'm Arne Peter-Castelline. |1239|: I'm a resident of CD1 and I'm also the LA Chapter Chair of the Equal Vote Coalition. |1240|: The Charter Commission has nominated both star voting and rank choice voting as topics for further study and I want to share my recommendation for star voting. |1241|: Star voting lets voters provide scores from 0 to 5 as opposed to rank choice voting where voters provide their first, second, third choice, et cetera. |1242|:  With the star ballot, voters can show their full and honest preference for each candidate, regardless of how many options are on the ballot. |1243|: In addition to showing their favorite, they can also show exactly how much they like their next favorite, whether it's a one-star candidate, a four-star candidate, or even a five-star candidate. |1244|: With star, that's allowed. |1245|: If a voter feels the same about multiple candidates, they can give them both the same score. |1246|: That means it's almost impossible to avoid a star voting ballot, and it also means voters can be as expressive as they please. |1247|:  If they want to give a nuanced opinion, that's great. |1248|: But if they just want to give fives to everyone in their party, that's also great. |1249|: I urge councils to support Start Voting if it's included in the council's recommendation. |1250|: Thank you all so much for your time.", "Embedding": [-0.00042242283, 0.058813218, -0.002566335, 0.04372127, -0.002041255, 0.04203858, 0.042303953, -0.007491817, -0.0061129658, 0.0019993917, 0.048752017, -0.0048373775, 0.0054187416, -0.039069016, -0.03751247, -0.018460842, 0.022546716, 0.047932412, 0.023287153, -0.0016882045, -8.4611565e-05, 0.0014885507, 0.031842086, 0.0071279835, -0.025004623, -0.038617127, -0.022338595, -0.04548734, 0.0073248586, -0.0069759577, 0.0036271922, -0.044588484, 0.005196682, -0.0008881618, 0.0036891273, -0.