{"ChunkNum": 68, "StartTime": 9325.589, "EndTime": 9426.051, "Content": "|1427|: Mr. President, colleagues, and all Angelenos, I invite you down to Point Furman Park in San Pedro tomorrow for the 31st annual Festival of Philippine Arts and Culture. |1428|: The festival was actually originally planned by the city's Department of Cultural Affairs back in 1990. |1429|: The first festival took place on Mother's Day, May 14, 1992, at LA City College. |1430|: Since then, it has grown exponentially. |1431|:  It moved to Cabrillo Beach in San Pedro in 94, and then Point Furman Park in 2001. |1432|: It did move to Echo Park in 2017, but we are proud in the 1-5 to have it back. |1433|: The 1-5 is grateful to host. |1434|: We hosted last year and tomorrow. |1435|: This year's theme translates from the Tagalog that I will not risk. |1436|:  to arm in arm reflecting the unity and the resilience of the Filipino-American community. |1437|: Please join us for vibrant performances that highlight incredible Filipino culture, music, art, and more. |1438|: There's also going to be plenty of great food, so please show up with an empty stomach. |1439|: The festival will begin at 10 a.m. |1440|: It will continue until 6 p.m. |1441|: Admission is free. |1442|:  Parking is limited, also free, but limited. |1443|: We encourage you to consider public transportation or use rideshare services. |1444|: We look forward to seeing you down in San Pedro in the 1-5 at Port Furman Park tomorrow. |1445|: And thank you to all of our great sponsors and underwriters for this beautiful event. |1446|: Thank you so much, Mr. Lee. |1447|:  Thank you, Mr. President.", "Embedding": [-0.00055436505, -0.03905699, -0.038400732, 0.035354875, -0.0024675583, -0.010913454, 0.076307155, -0.03126092, 0.005539056, -0.029018298, 0.002517543, -0.008991557, -0.00041980267, 0.005872465, 0.010480357, -0.021705896, -0.049988482, -0.053202957, -0.029340345, -0.008104621, -0.009557036, 0.0005361333, 0.049620215, 0.0010695356, 0.