{"ChunkNum": 78, "StartTime": 9870.92, "EndTime": 10194.389, "Content": "|1507|: Thank you. |1508|: Thank you, Mr. Blumenfield. |1509|: With that, Mr. Nazarian, thank you for this very important announcement and presentation today. |1510|: Any other announcements, members? |1511|: Seeing no other announcements, I'll ask everyone in the chambers to rise for adjourning motions. |1512|: And ask if there are adjourning motions to my left. |1513|:  I see you, Mr. Nazarian. |1514|: So I will begin with an adjourning motion. |1515|:  Colleagues, it's with heavy heart and a great spirit of sadness that I ask all of us to adjourn in the memory of the Honorable Robert Odell Knight, Sr. |1516|: He lived to the age of 89 years old, leaving a remarkable legacy of faith, dedication, and community service. |1517|: Mr. Knight was born in SoSo, Mississippi,\n|1518|:  In the 1930s, he was four of seven children. |1519|: He was raised on a working farm where you learn to work when the sun goes up and keep working until it goes down and your livelihood depends on your labor. |1520|:  He also was raised in a devout Christian family and church membership was a very important part of his life, later attending Oakwood College in Huntsville, Alabama. |1521|: And through his father's guidance, he applied his skills to plastering and construction and completed notable projects across the campus and throughout the city of Huntsville, Alabama. |1522|:  He served honorably in the United States Army in the late 1950s where he assisted a flight surgeon between Costa Rica, Panama, and Columbia. |1523|:  His time in Central America and South America broadened his worldview and allowed him to become bilingual in Spanish, a skill that would become very, very important in later years as he moved to the great city of Los Angeles in the 1960s. |1524|: He started a family here and began a dual career in elementary education and construction. |1525|:  While teaching in local schools, he continued to build homes and work with his brothers in the building trade. |1526|: And this is before people like Mr. Knight could be in the union and be a part of the big construction companies. |1527|: During the 1980s, the construction of the 105 freeway, also known as the Century Freeway,\n|1528|:  It prompted the relocation and demolition of numerous homes that were in its path and if you're old enough to remember there along imperial and a hundred between imperial and 120th all those houses that we lost Most in the 15th district, but some in in Athens and other parts of South La Robert saw an opportunity there through\n|1529|:  Will point out to this council a community benefits agreement one of the first ones that we ever had In the city of Los Angeles through a community benefits agreement Mr.. Knight was able to require acquire several of those homes at $1 apiece\n|1530|:  and had the ingenuity and the drive to figure out how to move them to other places. |1531|: So he had houses in West Adams, in South LA, in Inglewood, and other parts of Southern California. |1532|:  But his involvement didn't stop there. |1533|: Once he figured out he could move a house, he figured out he could then build a house. |1534|: And so he built houses throughout Southern California, single-family homes, multi-unit apartments, housing developments, and expanded his portfolio\n|1535|:  but never became a corporate landlord. |1536|: He was the kind of landlord that came personally and knocked on your door if something was broken and stayed there until the plumber or the painter or the fixer got things done. |1537|: He believed every person deserved a decent place to live, no matter how wealthy or how poor you were, and he worked to improve the lives of his tenant and was the kind of landlord that we all\n|1538|:  long for here in Southern California, not some big giant company across the country that, you know, maybe will take your call or maybe won't, but would show up when something went wrong with the apartments and would keep the apartments at a rate that working people could afford. |1539|: He helped stabilize neighborhoods, prevent displacement, and provided affordable options for people throughout the region. |1540|: Was an active member in his church,\n|1541|:  and built a great family network. |1542|: You can see all of the folks standing there on the east side of the gallery who've joined today to celebrate and commemorate the life and the gift of Mr. Knight. |1543|: I'm proud to be joined by his wife June and his children, his daughter Giselle and Nicole and his son Lonnie for this\n|1544|:  a journey motion. |1545|: I would be remiss, and it's a very difficult thing to do.", "Embedding": [-0.0007544061, -0.024078945, 0.030588927, -0.03273663, -0.002802921, 0.07299475, 0.022730052, 0.02495983, -0.006372567, -0.021798039, -0.058434255, 0.0007548326, -0.0011083813, 0.031910427, 0.044286698, 0.0072207535, 0.023009144, -0.020098379, 0.035576604, 0.0006913535, -0.010016469, -0.0070667085, 0.04780965, 0.03920313, 0.05811918, -0.014071876, -0.025910607, 0.020355033, -0.054774974, 0.04515001, -0.045815207, -0.07207174, 0.0067116334, 0.018103627, -0.0027779846, 0.016360618, 0.018210286, -0.0069819186, -0.005201153, 0.0047851205, -0.0067556067, 0.012797213, -0.035660807, 0.004951461, -0.003469265, -0.009289052, 0.009687266, -0.01239676, -0.0045238053, 0.009539456, 0.010525364, 0.007734718, -0.02247586, 0.0005408107, -0.018815583, 0.009648503, 0.017467098, -0.001397664, 0.014316248, 0.0013869756, 0.014105614, 0.005544151, 0.020569928, -0.02811443, -0.011964714, -0.018051162, 0.006058259, -0.031194905, -0.00492875, -0.014131751, -0.020591388, 0.018269015, -0.028858729, -0.016678033, -0.021431081, -0.005596463, -0.0056561935, 0.004606664, -0.014562677, -0.00042003207, -0.007320302, 0.008576705, -0.010021025, 0.02326036, -0.027906183, -0.014886297, -0.007586903, 0.005825939, 0.015566755, -0.010110611, 0.010209696, -0.035355352, 0.010436682, -2.6205826e-05, 0.0118